{"product_id": "39160", "page": 1, "page_order": 6, "recommended": false, "date": "2018-01-28", "text": "If you are thinking of buying this hoping it would be a modern version of Dungeon Siege 1 or 2, please do not.  It is virtually NOTHING like the first 2 in the series and almost every aspect of the game is miserable.  The camera angles(2) are both absolutely terrible.  The controls feel like you are trying to use a console controller on a game that was designed for mouse and keyboard... even when using a mouse and keyboard.  The \"stats\" have little to know clear meaning or explaination... that being said it's impossible to know what gear is better.  The maps are VERY linear, magnified by the minimap which is basically a straight line that you follow.  Little to no customization of your characater relative to the previous versions of the game.\nLong story short, do NOT buy this game, or the 3-game package.", "hours": 0.7, "user_id": "76561197964773915", "username": "Malfuseen", "products": 37, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 1, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-28", "text": "Wow!  What a gem, I purchased this game a few years ago and had wanted to get to it, but hadn't made the time.  Having played the first and second one this one blew it out of the water.  It's not open world, but very flexible in terms of moral and action choices - think Mass Effect + early Fable, at the end you get a great montage of how your actions impacted the future of the game.  It was hard to believe how good the graphics are for a 7 year old game.  Look forward to next edition.\nOnly gripes are that they need a better inventory system (selling and identfying what is on whom is rough) and improve on the key mapping descriptions - Key 1 equals power 1 should become Key 1 equals what ever the contextual power you have set the slot too.", "hours": 30.2, "user_id": "76561198014621099", "username": "DW2054", "products": 259, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 1, "page_order": 8, "recommended": false, "date": "2018-01-18", "text": "I haven't really got deep into the game but damn...  It really makes you not won't to keep going after 1 hour. Compared with DS 2 this game is one hell of a downgrade. What a shame.", "hours": 1.2, "username": "I'll stick you in my prayers", "products": 170, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 1, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-12", "text": "Combat has few buttons but is hard to master.\nNo doubt, that fans of Dungeon Siege I and II was dissapointed so much with this game.\nBecause here in order to win, you have to participate and not just click your way.\nKiting welcomes you at boss fights and higher difficulties.\nI remember you, Palefang, to get back to you at higher level!\nCo-op is fun, and fixed camera even helps to find your mate, so no way I'm unlocking it using console.\nBecause no one gets lost, and you should stick together anyway.\nI'm playing as Lukas in Co-op and blocking actually helps a lot, and often I ress my teammate if anything happens, and keep tanking.\nThis game in Co-op is like Dungeons in WoW, but only 2 people is enough.\nAlso, to save progress of Player 2, host should save to steam. For this case, save menu has special button in-game, at the bottom of the save window - steam saves. So save there and all the inventory and talent build will be saved for both players.\nIf player 1 wants to play singleplayer, and got huge level, then player 2 may join him in multiplayer while getting boost to the same level as player 1.\nDo I recommend Dungeon Siege III?\nYes!", "hours": 12.3, "user_id": "76561198072558133", "username": "Bubble", "products": 28, "early_access": false}
