{"product_id": "39160", "page": 7, "page_order": 9, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-07-09", "text": "The game is beautiful, and overall playable. The combat is very clunky though. Attacking roots you in place during the animation, which is used in other games but it's very noticeable in this one as there really is no fluid movement between attacking and dodging. The attack animations are very generic as well. Targeting is also very clunky, with all that is happening on screen you'll often find you're attacking the wrong direction. The story appears intriguing but is very straight forward. You know from the outset who the big bad is, with very little in the way of twists.\nOverall it's passable as an ARPG, but taking into account the legacy of the franchise, it feels more like a cash grab due to the name than an actual successor.", "hours": 15.2, "user_id": "76561198106202143", "username": "Silvrus", "products": 345, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 8, "page_order": 0, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-07-08", "text": "If you liked DS1 or DS2 do not get this game. It is nothing like the first two. Controls are clunky, options are limited, and the general game play is nothing like the first two games.\nIt might be fun in its own right, but I bought it excited about a third installment to the DS style and it came up severely lacking.", "hours": 2.9, "username": "Drakenbob", "products": 68, "early_access": false}
