{"product_id": "39160", "page": 57, "page_order": 9, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-08-11", "text": "Graphics? Acceptable. Sounds? Fair enough. Gameplay? Pretty bad with keyboard and mouse, so I switched to a controller, a bit better. So I'm playing this game, only on normal difficulty, and I keep asking myself: \"Why do I even bother?\" Even though I've purchased this game, I have absolutely zero intention of playing it again. I just can't get into it. Let alone the tedious walking from point A to point B, the respawning monsters and/or the loot system (which isn't very good either), the controls just kill it for me. I know my character isn't bad equipped, yet I keep dying because of control issues (bad response time, etc...). I just can't recommend this game. :(", "hours": 3.0, "username": "waraiotoko [\u7b11\u3044\u7537]", "products": 515, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 0, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-08-09", "text": "It's an ok way to pass the time, but there's nothing particularly interesting here. Combat gets pretty repetative and skills are poorly balanced. Not bad if if you're just looking for a Gauntlet-style slasher though.", "hours": 23.2, "username": "puppetsbane", "products": 140, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-08-08", "text": "this game while decent in terms of an RPG really didnt meet the expected standards of the first 2 dungeon seige games.  Both of those games are miles and miles above this one in all avenues from the leveling/skill systems to the way the game works.  Having set classes and even a distinct lack of character customization really makes this game feel like they took the world and the name but not the actual game its self and improved upon it.  It really is a shame since DS1 and 2 are imo some of the best tactcal/Action based RPGs of all time.   I remember when the first game was released and they used the seemingly endless no loading screen technology for the first time.  It blew me away that i could move from one point to another with out having to load and that i could complete the entire game with out a single load screen.  Moving down into a dungeon felt like it had real depth and the same went for DS2.\nIf you are looking for a decent RPG then this is an alright game, but if you are expecting the dungeon siege expience look elsewhere.", "hours": 2.2, "username": "Abeltensor", "products": 200, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 2, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-08-04", "text": "DS3 isn't like DS2 and DS. The game has been completly rethought for a console version (ps2 or ps3)... so does the pc version too. I have played both 1 and 2 and unfortunatly, the third isn't as good, and the experience fells very strange if you have played the trilogy.", "hours": 6.0, "user_id": "76561198056389390", "username": "Frankilled", "products": 319, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-08-04", "text": "This game gets a 9/10 for me, it got nice graphics plus very detailed physics, like items that move they way the should in the background, you can walk towards some chains and they will get pushed by your character (as they should). The game have a decent amount of spells, could maybe be like 5 more or something to each character, but still good with not so much to choose from (can get confusing with alot of spells). The quests have a nice story line, and they managed to make the side quests more well made, that you do a side quest butt you still fight a boss that give you great loot, you sometimes even get to a pace that you probably think is a main story place, but its not.\nAll the background content is well made and placed for it to flow in with the environment.\nThe times in quests were you get options on how you want to do things, like spare or kill someone and that makes it different for you in the game.\nOnly downsides that I can come up with is that you share the same screen (when you play with a friend), it would have been more fun if there were 2 separated screens, though in this shared screen way you get more \"team play\".\nGreat game, recommend to anyone that like rpg's!", "hours": 25.5, "username": "Mellowtech", "products": 141, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-08-03", "text": "Nice", "hours": 21.7, "username": "GuiltyMan", "products": 219, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 5, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-08-01", "text": "Tank controls and save points for a game released in 2011? No thank you.\nThe sale price I paid was too much.", "hours": 0.2, "username": "avenhelm", "products": 379, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 6, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-08-01", "text": "Has nothing to do with a good action RPG-game. The controls are totally designed for a controller pad and not for a classic mouse + keyboard setting. It feels very iffy and unprecise. Also the way you deveolpe your character is even more linear than in Diablo 3 after release. You just take every skill at the end - because there arent much anyway - and then just choose between 2 upgrade options. There is no real freedom in that game at all, but this is what defines a good RPG. I dont mean freedom story-wise that isnt really necessary, as linear stories can be as good as non-linear. But the way you approach that game in terms of gameplay is the worst I've seen in years. I payed 3 Euros for it at the Humble store and it was still too much money for a that game. Casual console gamers maybe could enjoy this but this game should have nevert been ported to the PC.", "hours": 0.7, "username": "High King Kallor", "products": 115, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 7, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-07-31", "text": "I bought this game when it first came out on the consoles. I was excited for it, as I was a big DS II fan. However this game plays nothing like its predecessor. That was a dungeon crawler similar to Neverwinter or even a team orientated Diablo. This is more of a straight action game. Each person has two weapons, and that is it. You never get a different type of weapon for them, only upgrades. What this means is combat is the same for the duration of the game. You do aquire different abilties, but that is about it. That would be fine if the combat was fun, however it never really managed that for me. In the last DS game you had a wide creative range on how to build your hero, in this one you are forced into a path depending on which avatar you want to play. If each hero had a unique story mode this might be worth it, however they all follow the same quests and maps. The only real difference is some conversation options, and a few videos. Think left 4 dead or dead island, there are different characters but the story is the same for everybody.\nI got this game on steam for free, so I installed it hoping after not playing DS II for years I would be more receptive to it. Not the case, the same issues still bother me. It feels like a shallow game to me, and a wasted opertunity. If you played the first two games, pass on this one. It will just bother you how different it feels.", "hours": 1.1, "username": "alwc37", "products": 177, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-07-30", "text": "Hilariously wooden voice acting with gravelly-voice-man doing the cut-scenes and fire-baby make for great laughs with friends. Just kind of annoying and awful without.\nThis game is hilariously bad, it's like one of those movies you watch with friends and laugh, a lot, about.\nLike, I don't care about any of the characters, the voice acting is half-wooden, switches between accents, and from time to time just sounds like someone ran Siri throuhg a Synthesizer.\nBut it's pretty frustratingly hilarious when you play it with a friend. I just don't recommend playing it alone, because as a single player game I would have just stopped playing after roughly 10 minutes.\nI also got it very cheap, so that factors into my 'this game was worth 5 dollars as a package deal with two other games that don't run on my computer because they're so old.'\nI haven't gotten to play dungeon siege I & II, but dungeon siege III is a barrel of (albeit unintentional) laughs.\n6/10, with friends.\nNot recommended without friends.", "hours": 8.0, "username": "Harbin", "products": 198, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 58, "page_order": 9, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-07-28", "text": "This isn't even remotely similar to earlier Dungeon Siege games.  If you're looking for something similar, stay away.  This game is a debacle.", "hours": 1.1, "user_id": "76561197982387765", "username": "Dead Already", "products": 49, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 59, "page_order": 0, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-07-25", "text": "I am very disappointed with this game! DO NOT BUY IT unless you have a game controler to use with your computer. The first and second games are click adventure simular to Diablo, this is not. It's a twitch response game with lots of button mashing. I found the keyboard contols far from useable and more frustarating then anything. I bought this game during the steam summer sale and am not regerting it. I should have spent my 10 bucks else where.", "hours": 1.8, "user_id": "76561197970511830", "username": "Out_Break", "products": 126, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "39160", "page": 59, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-07-19", "text": "This game man, wow, this game. Why is this such a buggy piece of steaming crap, is it because Square Enix is a bad publisher?", "hours": 1.0, "username": "TOFWHY", "products": 229, "early_access": false}
